Class MethodCallNode

  • public class MethodCallNode
extends IdentifierNode
    IdentifierNode extension that represents the declaration of a method call node type. See decodeStatement(TreeNode, String, Location) for more details on what correct inputs look like.

    • Method Detail

      • getArgumentListNode

        public ArgumentListNode getArgumentListNode()
        The the TreeNode that represents the arguments to the method call. For example:
         methodName(5, "Arg2", 3 * n);
        In the previous statement, the data within the parenthesis are the arguments passed to the method. The ArgumentNode returned by this method would contain a node for each of the arguments passed, in the correct order from left to right.
        Returns:
        The TreeNode that represents the arguments to the method call.

      • isExternal

        public boolean isExternal()
        Get whether or not the method is called externally. A method is external if it begins with an externally imported C file's name. For example:
         import "externalFile.h";
 
 ...
 
 public static void main(String args[])
 {
        // This is the external method call.
        externalFile.cFunctionName();
 }
        In this example, 'externalFile' is the C header file that is imported. 'cFunctionName()' is the name of a function that is contained within the imported header file.
        Returns:
        Whether or not the method is called externally.

      • hasVariableNode

      • getVariableNode

        public TreeNode getVariableNode()
        Get the TreeNode that represents the variable that contains the method. For example:
         ClassName obj = new ClassName();
 
 obj.methodName();
        In the previous statements, 'obj' is the variable and the method 'methodName()' is being called through the 'obj' variable.
        Returns:
        The TreeNode that represents the calling variable.

      • decodeStatement

        public static MethodCallNode decodeStatement(TreeNode parent,
                             java.lang.String statement,
                             Location location)
        Decode the given statement into a MethodCallNode instance, if possible. If it is not possible, this method returns null.
        To determine whether or not a method is called externally, refer to isExternal() for more details on what an external call looks like.
        Example inputs include:
        • methodName(5, varName, methodThatReturnsAValue(), "arg1")
        • externalFile.cFunctionName()
        • methodName('q', 5 * (2 / 3))
        Parameters:
        parent - The parent node of the statement.
        statement - The statement to try to decode into a MethodCallNode instance.
        location - The location of the statement in the source code.
        Returns:
        The generated node, if it was possible to translated it into a MethodCallNode.

      • decodeStatement

        public static MethodCallNode decodeStatement(TreeNode parent,
                             java.lang.String statement,
                             Location location,
                             boolean needsReference)
        Decode the given statement into a MethodCallNode instance, if possible. If it is not possible, this method returns null.
        To determine whether or not a method is called externally, refer to isExternal() for more details on what an external call looks like.
        Example inputs include:
        • methodName(5, varName, methodThatReturnsAValue(), "arg1")
        • externalFile.cFunctionName()
        • methodName('q', 5 * (2 / 3))
        Parameters:
        parent - The parent node of the statement.
        statement - The statement to try to decode into a MethodCallNode instance.
        location - The location of the statement in the source code.
        needsReference - Whether or not the method needs an object to reference where the method is located.
        Returns:
        The generated node, if it was possible to translated it into a MethodCallNode.
